Second version with additional variables

General notes.

  • I call all the IV predictors here. They are in %. i.e.Â 0.1 = 10%
  • R2 describes the goodness of fit and how much of the data can be fitted by the regression hyperplane. To compensate for different number of predictors, we only use R_adj to compare different models (of different size). Attention: R2 does not say if any predictors explain the data in the model. We can have quite a good R2 but no significant predictors, or predictors with small effects. In the non-significant cases, we can probably still draw a conclusion for the current sample though (but not generalise)
  • The correlations do not say anything about the goodnes of fit of the model in MLR.

Data

Marginal plots

Letâ€™s have a look at the data using marginal plots. This helps to see if any (potential) predictores are skewed. If this is the case, log() transformation will be applied in the regression model, which is a standard procedure to improve the model.

For the analysis of the RE data: P_ambition and S_coal are skewed to the right.

Ren_both_effects[["wide_no_na"]] <- Ren_both_effects[["wide_no_na"]]


EE_both_effects[["wide_no_na"]] <- EE_both_effects[["wide_no_na"]]

After transformation, it is still very skewed. Probably not good results if used.

Collinearity check

The selection of variables is essential. The preferred way is to have some theorethical knowledge from other studies. For a good model, there must no be any large collinearitie between variables.

All correlations above 0.8 are problematic. We donâ€™t find any. Letâ€™s also check this numerically based on the full (transfomred) model.

vif(full_models$RE$`01_untransformed`)
##       P_density      P_ambition           P_REN           S_GAV 
##        1.719549        1.998532        2.123838        3.516323 
##     S_potential        S_effort           S_PPS          S_elec 
##        3.553813        2.836066        4.512513        2.734632 
##         S_centr S_size_industry S_size_services 
##        1.816569        2.061526        2.465126

VIF above 5 is critical and above 10 dangerous. S_GAV and S_effort are slightly collinear, but no critical VIFs. We do not need to exclude any of our IVs.

Math variable selection

Letâ€™s apply a stepwise backward selectin of variables to the full model to improve things.

WARGNING: According to my stats script, â€œThere is a general rule of the thumb, saying that there should be at least 5 times as many observations as the number of coefficients that are estimated.â€. I.e. based on the 8 IV, there should be 40 observations, however, we only have 25 observations, so effectively this type of selection may not yield a good result, and hence we will also perfom stepwise selections with other subsamples (see below).

full_models[["RE"]][["03_selected"]] <- step(
  full_models[["RE"]][["01_untransformed"]], direction = "backward", trace = 0)
summary(full_models[["RE"]][["03_selected"]])

Checking Model assumptions

It is very important that some assumptions are fulfilled. Otherwise, the findings may be wrong and can not be generalised.

resplot(full_models[["RE"]][["03_selected"]])

  • Plot 1: The average error is probably 0 (within random resampled lines), which is good. There is no systematic error.
  • Plot 2: Redsiduals are normall distributed, which is good
  • Plot 3: There seems to be heteroskedasity, but random resampling suggests that this line could have be gotten by chance.
  • Plot 4: There arenâ€™t many influenctial cases. Good

All in all, statistical assumptions are fulfilled an the conclusions drawn from it are robust.

Method

We collected data for 28 countries for 3 dependent (DP), and X potentially explaning independent variables (IV); see table X. As some data was missing for some countries, we constructed multiple linear regression (MLR) models for 23 countreis to explain REN performance/ambition and 22 countries to explain EE performance/ambition. To avoid any collinearity, we analysed correlations between all independent variables (IV) and calculated variance inflation factors, but did not need to exclude any of the IV due to collinearity.

We constructed tested several models: - Full models include all of the IVs in Table X and the corresponding DV - Optimised models are constructed using a mathematical selection algorithm, namely a stepwise backward selection of variables which reduces a modelâ€™s AIC. - Policy models are only constructed using the policy group variables - Economic-context models are only constructed using the economic-context group variables

To check MLR assumptions, we analysed residual plots (Tukey-Anscombe, normal, scale-location and leverage plot). We used a random resampling approach to support our assumption analysis; i.e.Â we resampled new residuals to the existing fitted values, and hence were able to tell if any deviation from the optimal regression assumptions were systematic or random.

We use the 10% significance level, as also done byâ€¦ TODO!

LANA: I did some more analyses, if necessary they can also be added, but for now I would not include them.

Data

The data for the variables in Table X is a sample of all European countries. Hence, the sample is complete in terms of geographical coverage. However, due to missing values for certain variables, some countries could not be used in the MLR model construction. Also, the variables are often averaged values of certain years, and other samples may exist that are based on other years. Hence the main purpose of this statistical analysis is first to uncover which models could explain our DVs, and second, wheter these models are also valid if other samples were constructed.
